#X text 224 227 There can be advantages in using both [pattern] and [sequencer] \, like stochastically combining different rhythmic and melodic phrases \, whereas [score2] offers you a more fixed sequence \, and also easier to write \, read and use., f 52;
#X text 227 447 Like [score] \, chords and poliphonic events are possible if you split messages with commas. This object is better suited for monophonic scores or chords \, whereas [score] is more flexible for poliphonic events with independent duration for each event. You can subvert [score2] and also achieve something like that \, but it's just 'hacky'. Check its help file., f 55;
#X text 77 27 The [score2] object is a less versatile variant of [score] that follows the rhythmic notation paradigm of [pattern] and can substitute the combined usage of [pattern] and [sequencer]., f 76;
